@NODE Introduction "What is muLog ?"


	                         Introduction to muLog.
	                   ======================================
	muLog is a program for @{"MultiUser" LINK "MultiUser"} to enable you to log user's activities.
	To put it simply, it takes a string as an argument, and	appends the string
	to the MultiUser.log file in the config directory along with the UserID of
	the user who ran the log program, and the current date and time.
	   This would be pretty straight forward, but there is one problem. To allow
	all users to have write permissions on the MultiUser.log file, you could
	give all users write permission on the file, but this way anyone could
	easily delete the contents of the file.
	   Another alternative is to set the U bit in the protection field (set uid
	bit), and have the file owned by root. The problem with this method is that
	since root will own the log task (since the program is a suid program), it
	is impossible to find out who actually ran the log program.
	   What I decided to do is split muLog into two programs.

		1 => log.
	This program takes the string argument, finds the UserID of the current
	user, and gets the system time and date. It then passes this information
	onto the other program logd. log has no special permissions on the
	MultiUser.log file, so it can't write to the log file directly.

	   2 => logd.
	This log Daemon runs in the background, and waits for a message from the
	log program. When it receives the message, it appends the string to the
	MultiUser.log file. logd is a suid program (the U bit set), and is owned
	by root. This means that logd has the access rights to any file on the
	system. After it receives the message, and appends it to the MultiUser.log
	file, it simply goes back to sleep and waits for the next message.

@ENDNODE

@NODE Installation "How to install muLog."


	                    How to install muLog.
          	          ========================

	    IMPORTANT : You *MUST* be logged in as root to properly install muLog.
	To install, you can either use the provided installation script which uses
	the IconX program. Alternatively, if you have problems with the script
	(or don't trust my installation script), you can do it manually
	as follows.

	Copy log c:           ; The two binaries.
	Copy logd c:          ;
	SetOwner c:log root   ; If you are loged in as root, these 2 lines shouldnt be necessary.
	SetOwner c:logd root
	MProtect c:log rewd GROUP re OTHER re      ; Normal permissions.
	MProtect c:logd urewd GROUP re OTHER re    ; Set the U bit (IMPORTANT).

	If you want the log daemon to be run every boot-up :

	Add the following line to S:User-Startup.
	run >nil: c:logd  ; This will run the daemon in the background.

@ENDNODE

@NODE Usage "How to use muLog."

	                            Using muLog
         	                  ==============

	To use muLog, first of all you need to have the daemon running. Personally, I
	run this at bootup, but you can also do it manually with 
	      run >nil: c:logd
	Running logd while another logd program is already running will signal the
	daemon to quit. Running it again will start it up again.

	Once logd is running, you can use the log program to append to the log file.
	It only takes one argument (a string).
	      e.g.
	             c:log Testing the log daemon
	      will append something like the following to the MultiUser.log file.
             29-Oct-95, 21:33:52: logd: 'root' Testing the log daemon

	          date     , time    : logd: 'userid' log string


	It is not intended that this program be used from the shell prompt, it would
	not make sense to do so. But, it is useful if you have something like
	ToolsDaemon running with customised menus. You can then monitor the activites
	of less experienced users on your system who use the menus to launch their
	programs. Or, you could put it in shell scripts, e.g. in the S:Shell-Startup
	file to find out when and what users are using the shell etc.

@ENDNODE

@NODE Requirements "What do you need to use muLog"

	                What you need to use muLog
	               ============================
	You just need to have @{"MultiUser" LINK "MultiUser"} installed. There are no other
	special requirements.

@ENDNODE

@NODE MultiUser "MultiUser File System"

	                What is MultiUser File System (muFS)
	              =======================================
	Introduction
	============

	MultiUser allows you to create a *IX-like environment where several users live
	together  in harmony, unable to delete each others files, unable to read those
	private  love-letters  of  other  users.   And  this even if several users are
	working on the machine at the same time (on a terminal hooked up to the serial
	port)

	People without a valid login ID and password won't be able to access files you
	have made private with MultiUser.  If you make all files private (not readable
	for others), the only useful thing they could do, is boot from a floppy.


	Distribution
	============

	MultiUser Release 1.8 is distributed in 3 archives:

	   MultiUser18_bin.lha:   Basic MultiUser package (you really need this!)
	   MultiUser18_api.lha:   Include files, autodoc, etc...
	   MultiUser18_src.lha:   Source for the library and support commands

	There  is  no  new  distribution of the external utilities; use the archive
	from the 1.7 release: MultiUser17_ext.lha

	For  more information about MultiUser (disclaimer, distributability, usage,
	etc...),  read  the  documentation  file  'MultiUser.doc'  in  the  archive
	'MultiUser18_bin.lha'.

	===========================================================================
	           MultiUser © Copyright 1993-1994 by Geert Uytterhoeven

